Section 1:
HCR 100 Text skip navigation SENATE PRESIDENT SENATORS COMMITTEES VIDEO/AUDIO DISTRICT MAPS SENATE CLERK SENATE RULES HOUSE SPEAKER DELEGATES COMMITTEES VIDEO/AUDIO DISTRICT MAPS HOUSE CLERK HOUSE RULES HOUSE STAFF JOINT INTERIM COMMITTEES LEGISLATIVE ADMINISTRATOR LEGISLATIVE SERVICES DIVISION PUBLIC INFORMATION LEGISLATIVE AUTOMATED SYSTEMS DIVISION LEGISLATIVE AUDITOR'S OFFICE PERFORMANCE EVALUATION & RESEARCH DIVISION POST AUDIT DIVISION BUDGET DIVISION REGULATORY AND FISCAL AFFAIRS DIVISION CLAIMS COMMISSION CRIME VICTIMS RULE-MAKING REVIEW SPECIAL INVESTIGATIONS JUDICIAL COMP. COMMISSION JOINT RULES STAFF INFO BILL STATUS BILL STATUS BILL TRACKING STATE LAW WEST VIRGINIA CODE ACTS OF THE LEGISLATURE CODE OF 1931 WV CONSTITUTION US CONSTITUTION REPORTS AGENCY REPORTS AGENCY GRANT AWARDS PERFORMANCE EVALUATIONS POST AUDITS EDUCATIONAL CITIZEN’S GUIDE INTERNSHIP PROGRAM PAGE PROGRAM PUBLICATIONS PHOTO GALLERY CAPITOL HISTORY HOW A BILL BECOMES LAW CONTACT SENATE ROSTER HOUSE ROSTER PUBLIC INFO. NEWS RELEASES HELPFUL LINKS Introduced Version - Originating in Committee House Concurrent Resolution 100 History |  Email Key: Green = existing Code. Red = new code to be enacted HOUSE CONCURRENT RESOLUTION 100(By Delegates Amos, Anders, Burkhammer, Chiarelli, Clark, W., Dean, Drennan, Hall, Hamilton, Heckert, Hite, Jeffries, Lewis, Masters, Mazzocchi, Miller, Petitto, Pinson, Pushkin, Smith, D., Stephens, Vance, Willis, and Worrell)[Originating in Standing Committee on Health and Human Resources; Reported on April 8, 2025 ] Requesting the Joint Committee on Government and Finance to study cooperative agreements and hospital pricing transparency in the State of West Virginia. Whereas, Oversight of anticompetitive pricing practices and hospital mergers is essential to ensuring fair market competition and consumer protection; and Whereas, Nationwide many healthcare provider markets have become highly concentrated, with data indicating provider consolidation leads to increased prices as much as 40%; and Whereas, There are many areas in West Virginia where patients have only one choice for their health care because the previously independent hospitals, facilities, and physician practices have been purchased; and Whereas, Research has shown that competition in health care provider and payer markets promotes higher quality, lower cost health care, greater access to care, increased innovation, higher wages and better benefits for health care workers; and Whereas, Across the country, unsustainable healthcare inflation due to growing consolidation in the healthcare sector has put a strain on both public and private budgets and limited patient access; and Whereas, Increased oversight of hospital pricing has the potential to foster competition, reduce healthcare costs, and improve patient outcomes; and Whereas, Antitrust oversight of health care consolidation is a vital control against anticompetitive practices and the Federal Trade Commission and the Attorney General play a key role in monitoring and enforcing laws related to anticompetitive behavior in the healthcare industry; and Whereas, The federal Hospital Price Transparency Rule requires hospitals to make pricing information publicly available, yet concerns persist regarding the accessibility, accuracy, and clarity of such information; and Whereas, President Trump’s Justice Department recently launched an Anticompetitive Regulations Task Force to study healthcare markets that encourage overbilling and consolidation; therefore, be it Resolved by the Legislature of West Virginia: That the Joint Committee on Government and Finance is hereby requested to conduct a study on hospital pricing transparency and cooperative agreement laws, including but not limited to the effectiveness of current hospital price disclosure requirements, the extent to which hospitals comply with federal and state transparency laws, and potential legislative or regulatory improvements to enhance oversight of anticompetitive practices; and, be it Further Resolved, That the study shall include an assessment of hospital mergers and acquisitions in West Virginia, their impact on pricing and competition, and the role of the Federal Trade Commission and the Attorney General in overseeing such activities; and, be it Further Resolved, That the Joint Committee on Government and Finance report its findings, conclusions, and recommendations, together with drafts of any legislation necessary to effectuate its recommendations, to the Legislature during the regular session of 2026; and, be it Further Resolved, That the expenses necessary to conduct this study, prepare a report, and draft necessary legislation be paid from legislative appropriations to the Joint Committee on Government and Finance. Bill Status  | Bill Tracking  | Legacy WV Code  | Bulletin Board  | District Maps  | Senate Roster  | House Roster  | Live  | Blog  | Jobs  | Links  | Home This Web site is maintained by the West Virginia Legislature's Office of Reference & Information.  | Terms of Use | Webmaster | © 2025 West Virginia Legislature ** Print On Demand Name: Email: Phone:


